sqlcode_0 = "SELECT dim_date.date_value, dim_date.`quarter number`, dim_date.holiday,dim_date.workingday,fact_weather.temp_average,fact_weather.temp_high, fact_weather.humid_average,fact_weather.wind_average, dim_date.`month name`, dim_date.year,  t.customer_count as casual,t1.subscriber_count as registered,(t.customer_count+t1.subscriber_count) as count FROM (select COUNT(distinct trip_id) as customer_count, trip_date FROM fact_trip WHERE usetype ='Customer' group by trip_date) t join (select COUNT(distinct trip_id) as subscriber_count, trip_date FROM fact_trip WHERE usetype ='Subscriber' group by trip_date) t1 on t.trip_date=t1.trip_date JOIN fact_weather ON t.trip_date = fact_weather.dim_date_date_value JOIN dim_date ON dim_date.date_value = t.trip_date"
cursor.execute(sqlcode_0)
result_0 = cursor.fetchall()
df0=pd.DataFrame(result_0)
print(df0)

#Make a correlation diagram between multiple continuous variables,compare the relationship between any two continuous
#variables. It can be clearly seen in the figure that temp and mtemp are roughly linear,
#but there is also a set of data that deviates significantly from the linear correlation trend,
#which may be related to humidity and wind speed. Therefore, it can be considered that temp, 
#humidity and windspeed jointly determine mtemp

fig , axes = plt.subplots(1,3,figsize = (24,8))

sn.regplot(df['temp'] , df['count'] , ax = ax1)
sn.regplot(df['humidity'] , df['count'] , ax = ax2)

ax2.set_title('The influence of humidity')
ax3.set_title('The influence of windspeed')
#Although the influence of the three weather factors on the number
#of leases is relatively scattered, it can be clearly seen that
#temperature and wind speed are positively correlated with the number 
#of leases, and humidity is negatively related to the number of leases.
